Step 4 : Testing the importance of the regression

Summary_Model <- summary(relation)  # the model summary should be saved as an object.
coefficients_Model <- Summary_Model$coefficients  # Coefficients
Estimate_of_ <- coefficients_Model["indata$x", "Estimate"]  # Obtain a beta speed estimate.
Standard_Error <- coefficients_Model["indata$x", "Std. Error"]  # Obtain standard Error for speed
t_value <- Estimate_of_/Standard_Error  # Need to calculate t
t_value
## [1] 11.04673
qt(p = .025, df = 48)
## [1] -2.010635

When |t|>=|t_0.05,48|, we reject the null hypothesis is rejected at a 5% level of significance.According to the output of the t-distribution, |t|>=|t_0.05,48| is equal to |9.132449|>|-2.010635|.Therefore we can rule out the null hypothesis and determine that the regression line fitted to the data is significant.

When = 0.01

qt(p = .005, df = 48)
## [1] -2.682204

When |t|>=|t_0.01,48|, the null hypothesis is rejected at a 1% level of significance. and we obtain |t|>=|t_0.05,48| as |9.132449|>|-2.682204| from the output of the t-distribution.We therefore rule out the null hypothesis and determine that the regression line fitted to the data is significant.

Step 7 : Using underroot of y as the response, find a simple linear regression model

indata$underroot_of_y <- sqrt(indata$y)
model_underroot_of_y <- lm(underroot_of_y ~ x, data = indata)
summary(model_underroot_of_y)
##

Need to make Regression Visual

model_underroot_of_y %>% ggplot(aes(x = x, y = underroot_of_y)) +

## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Need to plot a residual

residuals_new <- model_underroot_of_y$residuals
new_y_hat <- model_underroot_of_y$fitted.values
plot(new_y_hat, residuals_new, xlab = "Fitted values", ylab = "Residuals",
main = "Residual plot")

Output : According to the converting models regression coefficients, the square root of the response variable underroot_y is expected to rise by 0.0009712 units for every unit increase in the predictor variable x (monthly usage).This models residual plot demonstrates that the residuals variance is essentially consistent across the range of fitted values, which suggests that the transformation has stabilized the inequality of variance issue mentioned in step 6 and prevented it from occurring again.
